snippet.textDisplay:
I didn't (and don't plan to) see Birds of Prey for a bunch of reasons. #1 is that DC has consistently demonstrated that they have no idea how to make an entertaining superhero movie. One successful divergent blip (in a totally different theme/mood from the superhero genre as a whole) doesn't change that. I gave up on DC movies after Man of Steel, and I won't waste money on opening weekend on them again. In particular, DC has proven extra incompetent when it comes to hero ensemble movies, which this is. I'm still baffled at how they took so many cool characters and managed to chew them up and spit them out into whatever the hell Justice League was supposed to be.
Lastly, it felt super pandering. I'm a feminist and a woman. I love superhero movies. I love female empowerment movies. All of the marketing for this movie felt like some old executive dude in drag saying "no, gurls, I TOTES get you, I'm so hip to the haps, gurlz". Like pretty much every movie they make, this felt like an attempt by DC to read the market, cherrypick random elements they think make for big bucks, and slap them together into a hit (which, clearly, has not worked for them so far). If Birds of Prey turns out to not be that then I'm thrilled, and I'll see it, but nothing about the lead-up to this film made me feel like it was anything but a totally disingenuous (and even sort of condescending) pink-washing money grab.

snippet.textDisplay:
Why I didn't see Birds of Prey:
- I didn't know about it until probably a week ago when I saw Margot's interview on Hot Ones
- I don't care for Harley Quinn. I love the actress that plays her, but I don't want to see a movie dedicated to someone who's always been a secondary or tertiary character for me.
- I haven't been in the mood to see a movie in theatres. I'll probably watch this in the future at some point. It's just like comic books: I'm not always in the mood and I don't care for every character. I like SOME comics and I read them when I'm in the mood. It just so happened that this movie released at a point where I wasn't in the mood and the movie industry needs to stop freaking out over opening day numbers because I just don't find myself in the mood for that kind of movie at all times.

snippet.textDisplay: Why didn't I see Birds of Prey? Two reasons. One, for as much as I loved Harley Quinn in Suicide Squad as one of the few good things about that film, Suicide Squad still sucked. Two, the advertising for this film was garbage. That's really about it, and the things I've heard since then don't exactly inspire confidence in the quality of the film. From producers blaming men for the movie's failure, to blaming the fucking coronavirus, to a bunch of idiots/bots on Twitter blasting the Sonic movie to try and help Birds of Prey, like they did against Venom when that came out. So yeah, at this point, I'm not watching Birds of Prey on principle more than anything else.
